  "text": "Nature Video 11 June 2025 The new method could be 70 times faster than repairing painting by hand. You have full access to this article via your institution. A researcher in MIT's Mechanical Engineering Department has found a way to restore paintings quickly, by creating physical masks from digitally restored artworks.Read the paper: Physical restoration of a painting with a digitally constructed maskIt’s estimated that around 70% of the art in institutional collections is damaged and hidden away from public view. In part that’s because of the often prohibitive costs to restore old paintings.The researcher estimates this technique could be up to 70 times faster than repairing the art by hand, something they hope will lead to more painting going on display.Subscribe to Nature Briefing, an unmissable daily round-up of science news, opinion and analysis free in your inbox every weekday. doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-01836-z Related Articles How AI is revealing the language of the birds ChatGPT has a language problem — but science can fix it What ChatGPT is and what it's not: a three minute guide AI finally beats humans at a real-life sport - drone racing AI and robotics demystify the workings of a fly's wing The AI historian: A new tool to decipher ancient texts Subjects Latest on:",
